DSCI 100 Final Project Report¶

Introduction¶

Cardiovascular disease is the leading cause of death across the world for both men and women. The diagnosis of heart disease is often based on previous experience of diagnosing patients with similar symptoms, signs, physical examinations and current clinical tests. Several factors, such as smoking habits, body cholesterol levels, obesity, high blood pressure and lack of physical exercise increase the risk of heart disease. Patients suffering from heart disease require timely diagnosis of their condition, early treatment and constant observation. A difficult challenge that health organizations, namely hospitals and medical centers face, is the efficient diagnosis of patients through non-expensive and non-invasive means. Our model aims to extract patterns and relationships by identifying classifiers with the highest accuracy associated with heart disease from previously collected data to predict whether or not a patient has heart disease; therefore, it can be helpful to medical professionals to make timely clinical diagnoses and decisions.

For the purposes of our analysis, we will define a patient having heart disease as fatty plaques narrowing the diameter of blood vessels by 50% or greater, as physicians formally diagnose patients with obstructive heart disease at this benchmark because this deems patients at a high enough risk of a heart attack or stroke to warrant preventative measures.

Dataset:¶

In this analysis we will utilize a dataset from the UCI Machine Learning Repository with data collected by 4 institutes:

  1. Hungarian Institute of Cardiology. Budapest: Andras Janosi, M.D.
  2. University Hospital, Zurich, Switzerland: William Steinbrunn, M.D.
  3. University Hospital, Basel, Switzerland: Matthias Pfisterer, M.D.
  4. V.A. Medical Center, Long Beach and Cleveland Clinic Foundation: Robert Detrano, M.D., Ph.D.

This data set provides various heart and health related observations to utilize in relation to heart disease in humans. Any abbreviations not immediately obvious that are utilized within the dataset will be clarified at the first instance necessary, as well as within the Glossary
at the bottom of the file.

Question: Given a set of factors pertaining to an individual, will they have heart disease?¶

Predictors¶

Removal of non-numeric data¶

In order to create the best model, we need to optimize our choice of predictors. We can start by removing non numerical data, since it is too difficult to compute the distance of classes. A solution we tried to use to simplify classes was to assign them values. For example, if an observation can have 3 traits, then we can assign those 3 traits to the numericaL values 1, 2 and 3. However, classes are not always on a spectrum, but can be completely arbitrary and mutually exclusive, meaning that if a trait is more of 3, that does not make it closer to 2 than 1. Therefore, we've decided to remove them.

Missing Values¶

We can observe in Table 1.1 that the table has each variable in a column, and each observation in a row. However, from the preview above, we can see that the value for some traits of particular observations are the charactor "?", which we can assume are missing values since they don't correspond with the rest of the items in the column. We can eliminate this issue by filtering out all the observations that have a "?" value in a variable/predictor we use.

Splitting Sex¶

In the making of our model, we decided to split our data set by sex, as men and women have different levels of target blood pressure ranges, max heart rates and cholesterol levels. For example, younger women tend to have lower LDL cholesterol levels than young men, then after puberty, women tend to have higher HDL cholesterol levels than men because estrogen boosts cholesterol. Furthermore, women over 55 or who have completed menopause tend to have lower LDL cholesterol levels than men and in general, men tend to have higher HDL cholesterol levels than women. Additionally, women tend to have lower target blood pressure ranges compared to men. Lastly, heart disease tends to develop in women 7 to 10 years later than in men due to exposure to estrogens during the fertile period of life which delays heart disease in women. Therefore, we hypothesis that the physioloigcal differences between men and women may negatively influence predictions made.

In [175]:
# Filters the unknown data in relevant columns and standardizes column types and values
heart_disease_filtered <- filter(heart_disease_cleveland, resting_bp != "?", chol != "?", oldpeak != "?", max_hr != "?", num != "?") %>%
    select(sex, age, max_hr, oldpeak, chol, resting_bp, num) %>%
    mutate(max_hr = as.numeric(max_hr), oldpeak = as.numeric(oldpeak), chol = as.numeric(chol), resting_bp = as.numeric(resting_bp)) %>%
    mutate(num = ifelse(num > 0, 1, 0)) %>%
    mutate(num = factor(num))

The filtered columns are then piped into a select funtion, which selects a range of columns age, sex, resting_bp, chol and num, to be used for our analysis. The selected rows are passed to the mutate function, where the values are turned into numeric values so they can be graphed later. We then mutate the num colum, using ifelse, which assignes the value in the column num to either 1, if the value in the colum is greater than 0, and 0 if the value is less than 0. We do this because we decided to only measure if a patient has heart disease or not, and the num column includes 2, which means that 2 or more arteries have shrunk greater than 50% in diameter. The column num is then turned into a factor.

Shown in table 2.1 above, we can see a strong difference in the average cholesterol levels for men and women. In men without heart disease, we found and average of 231.59 mg/dl in men, while woman had an average of 256.7500 mg/dl. This difference becomes even more distinct when comparing men and woman who are classified to have heart disease. In men with heart disease, they are shown to have an average of 246.06 mg/dl, while in woman they are shown to have an average of 276.16, which is a difference on average of roughly 30 mg/dl. Additionally, by doing this analysis, we can confirm our hypothesis that men and woman have different physiological tolerances, and therefore by seperating the data we can create more accurate classifiers.

Building the classifier¶

We then split our data into a training and testing set. This is done so we can assess the model on how it is going to predict unseen data on new data points that arent labelled. We need to be split our data because if you use the same data that you used to fit the model, your assessment is biased in favour of the model and your model will be more accurate than it is because it has access to the labels.

In [189]:
men_split <- initial_split(data = heart_disease_men, prop = .8, strata = num)
women_split <- initial_split(data = heart_disease_women, prop = .8, strata = num)

We use .8 as our proportion value in order to later use a 5 fold cross validation. The .8 proportion allows us to cover our entire dataset, as .2 times 5 is the whole proportion 1.

create_recipe <- function(dat) {
    recipe(num ~ ., data = dat) %>%
    step_scale(all_predictors()) %>%
    step_center(all_predictors())
}

Having defined the cross validation for each sex's table, we can define our recipe here in order to find the best choice for the k-nearest neighbours prediction.

In [198]:
grid_vfold <- tibble(neighbors = 1:25)

create_workflow <- function(rec, mod) {
    workflow() %>%
    add_recipe(rec) %>%
    add_model(mod)
}

knn_results <- function(rec, mod, vf) {
    create_workflow(rec, mod) %>%
    tune_grid(resamples = vf, grid = grid_vfold) %>%
    collect_metrics()
}

We create a tibble of the possible k values to run a cross-validation for a grid of numbers of neighbors ranging from 1 to 25 called grid_vfold. We create a function called create_workflow that adds the model specification and recipe. Then we use the tune_grid function to fit the model for each value in a range of parameter values after applying the workflow, and tune our neighbors using the grid of values we made.

In [199]:
knn_results_men <- knn_results(men_recipe, knn_tune, vfold_men)
knn_results_women <- knn_results(women_recipe, knn_tune, vfold_women)

The workflow and the tune_grid function is applied to the different data frames for men and women.

                  geom_point() +
                  geom_line() +
                  labs(x = 'Neighbors', y = 'Accuracy Estimate') +
                  theme(text = element_text(size = 10)) +
                  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 100, by = 5))
}

Having obtained the best accuracy values, we can now use them to test our vfold's accuracy. We'll do that using a fit and the collect_metrics function.

In [208]:
create_fit <- function(k, rec, traindat) {
    knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = k) %>%
        set_engine("kknn") %>%
        set_mode("classification")
    pfit <- workflow() %>%
        add_recipe(rec) %>%
        add_model(knn_spec) %>%
        fit(data = traindat)
}
prediction_accuracy <- function (pfit, testdat) {
    test_predictions <- predict(pfit, testdat) %>%
        bind_cols(testdat)
}

We then create a function that creates are K nearest neighbors classifer, sets k = to the one with the best accuracy, creates a model specification, ombine the model specification and recipe into a workflow, and then finally use fit with the training data to build the classifier. We then create a function that uses our K-nearest neighbour classifier object to predict the class labels for our test set. Bind_cols is used to add the column of predictions to the original test data.

hd_women_fit <- create_fit(women_k_best_accuracy, women_recipe, women_training)

The functions created above are then applied to the men and women data frames.

Discussion¶

Summary:¶

Our resulting classifier had an accuracy for 72.5% in men, as well as an accuracy for 77.7% in woman. Generally speaking, for circumstances as serious as human health, one would generally say that an accuracy of roughly 75, or 3/4 guesses would not be accurate enough. However, since we only use a select few variables in building our classifier that all record data through non-invasive means, this classifier may be useful if there is no other means to diagnose a patient.

We began our data analysis by removing all observations that were classification parameters rather than numerical ones. After that we found the variables that when analyzed brought about a plausible model for generating a classification system for heart disease. These are: blood pressure, cholesterol, age, maximum heart rate, and ST wave depression induced by exercise. The analysis followed that cholesterol increases blood pressure, which in turn increases ST wave depression. This variable is a measurement of strain on the heart induced by exercise. This, of course, correlates extremely well with the type of heart disease we are measuring, which is narrowing of major arteries, which in turn would put a major strain on the heart. Uniquely women are not as heavily affected by this variety of heart disease, and it seems to skew our model to appear more accurate due to the majority not having it. This may because that woman are twice as likely to have nonobstructive heart disease compared to men, and make up much of the undertreated population of heart disease pateints. This would explain why in Table 2.1, woman would appear to have a much higher tolerance to cholerterol and the diagnosis of heart disease. Since we classified our prediction to be based off of the narrowing of the major blood vessels, many woman would be underdiagnosed since they are much more susceptible to non-obstructive heart diseases than obstrutive. This woud explain why in our confusion matrix, only 2 woman are accurately diagnosed to have heart disease. There are many woman who may have non-obsctruvtive heart disease, but since our classifier only measures the narrowing of blood vessels, and classifies having heart disease as such, they would go untreated. However, there is evidence that non-obstructive heart disease are at the same risk of death due to heart attacks, stroke, or heart failure, as people with their major arteries blocked, which would explain why many woman with heart disease go untreated.

Expected outcomes and Significance:¶

We anticipated to find that high blood pressure, high cholesterol, and age to all be strongly linked. In graphs 2.2, 2.3, 2.4, we can see a positive weak correlation between all of them, meaning that they are less closely tied that we had anticipated. However, the relationship is there, which is to be expected since their values are typically reflective of a general lifestyle one lives. For example, the older you get, the less likely you are to exercise regularly and maintain a lower blood pressure. Additionally, we expected to find a positive relationship between blood pressure and the ST wave depression induced by exercise, since it intuitively makes sense for there to be a stronger strain when someone doesn't regularly exercise does do so, which we found to be true. Lastly, we had hypothesized that the there be physiological differences in men and woman which may skew our data, which we also found to be true in table 2.1 when we compared the cholersterol levels.

What impact could such findings have?¶

According to dieticians and researchers, heart disease is preventable and can be reversed. Moderate changes to diet can be enough to prevent it early on, and reversal can be achieved through cardiac rehabilitation. By noticing patterns and trends in easily tracked factors such as blood pressure and cholesterol levels, one can take the steps necessary to prevent or reverse the disease. Therefore, despite the innaccuacy of our classifier at around 75%, it uses numerical data that is relatively easy to collect. By more frequently checking up on these variables, an earliar diagnosis may be found which would leave more time for patients to receive treatment. Additionally, since many woman are being untreated since they are more vulenrable to non-obstructive heart disease than obstructive heart disease, different measurements and considerations should be used to diagnose woman.

What future questions could this lead to?¶

How do we accurately predict which individuals are more at risk of getting heart disease using more factors?
What symptoms and factors are most strongly correlated to preventable/reversable heart disease?
Which symptoms and factors most strongly correlate to early signs of heart disease?
Why are woman twice as likely to have non-obstructive heart disease compared to men?

Conclusion:¶

By analyzing this data set, we hope to find and support the traditional narrative surrounding heart disease and its causes. Furthermore, we hope that this can give insight as to the aspects of our lives that most strongly impact our risk for heart disease, giving a guideline as to what to fix if you believe you are at risk.

Glossary¶

  • Age - Age in years
  • Sex - 1 = Male, 2 = Female
  • chest_pain - Chest Pain
    • 1 = Typical Angina - Typical squeezing heart pain, associated with emotional or physical stress
    • 2 = Atypical Angina - Less predictable heart pain, usually stabbing, piercing, etc.
    • 3 = Non-anginal Pain - Pain unassociated with angina in the chest
    • 4 = Asymptomatic - No pain
  • resting_bp - Resting blood pressure in
  • chol - Cholesterol levels in mg/dl
  • fasting_bs - Blood sugar when fasting is greater than 120 mg/dl, 1 = TRUE, 2 = FALSE
  • resting_ecg - Resting heart rate measured using an ecg
    • 0 = Normal heart reading
    • 1 = ST-T wave abnormality readings (abnormal ecg wave), indicative of complications
    • 2 = Probable/definite left ventricular hypertrophy (thickening of the walls of the heart)
  • max_hr - Maximum heart rate achieved
  • exangina - Exercise induced angina experienced, 1 = TRUE, 0 = FALSE
  • oldpeak - ST wave depression induced by exercise compared to rest
  • slope - The slope of the peak exercise ST segment
    • 1 = upsloping
    • 2 = flat (healthy)
    • 3 = downsloping
  • ca - number of major vessels (0-3) colored by flourosopy
  • thal - 3 = normal; 6 = fixed defect; 7 = reversable defect
  • num - the predicted attribute - diagnosis of heart disease (angiographic disease status) (Value 0 = < 50% diameter narrowing; Value 1 = > 50% diameter narrowing)
